    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1963-07-20T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1963-07-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="14"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d14">
                <head>14. Memorandum from Read (<gloss target="#t_SS_1">S/S</gloss>) to <persName
                        corresp="#p_BM_1">McGeorge Bundy</persName>, July 20<note n="1"
                        type="source" xml:id="d14fn1">Transmits memorandum on the situation in
                        Bolivia. Confidential. 2 pp. Kennedy Library, National Security Files,
                        Countries Series, Bolivia, General 4–7/63.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <date ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-head" calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1963-07-20">July 20, 1963</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <pb facs="d14-1" n="1" type="facsimile" xml:id="d14-1"/>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>The Situation in Bolivia</item>
                </list>
                <p>In reference to Mr. <persName corresp="#p_SB_1">Bromley Smith</persName>’s oral
                    request to Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MEM_1">Martin</persName> today, I am
                    forwarding herewith a memorandum on the situation in Bolivia.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>D. Rowe (for) <lb/> Benjamin Reed</signed>
                    <affiliation>Executive Secretary</affiliation>
                </closer>
                <pb facs="d14-2" n="2" type="facsimile" xml:id="d14-2"/>
                <pb facs="0211" n="36" type="typeset" xml:id="pg_36"/>
                <frus:attachment>
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">
                        <hi rend="strong">Enclosure</hi>
                    </note>
                    <list type="subject">
                        <head>SUBJECT</head>
                        <item>The Situation in Bolivia</item>
                    </list>
                    <p>In our discussions with Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_SBS_1"
                            >Stephansky</persName> during his recent consultation the developments
                        reported in La Paz telegrams 93 and 99, dated July 19, were foreseen. Our
                        planning, based on the Ambassador’s conversations with President <persName
                            corresp="#p_PEV_1">Paz</persName> and the recommendations resulting
                        therefrom, has provided for financial assistance, [<hi rend="italic">less
                            than 1 line not declassified</hi>] and for equipment. The question of
                        possible need for United States personnel did not arise. Under our
                        contingency planning a special fund of $4,000,000 has been set up, and in
                        response to an emergency request received yesterday $325,000 has been
                        authorized for two projects to assist in the mining area.</p>
                    <p>The Ambassador’s analysis to date has not indicated that armed intervention
                        was likely to be required in the confrontation which we have expected as a
                        result of President <persName corresp="#p_PEV_1">Paz</persName>’ apparent
                        decision to enforce labor discipline in the mines. While we are not
                        surprised that General Barrientos has suggested that Special Forces might be
                        needed to back up the Bolivian Armed Forces (Embassy telegram 93) we should
                        not take his démarche too seriously until we have had a further report and
                        recommendation based on Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_SBS_1"
                            >Stephansky</persName>’s forthcoming conversation with President
                            <persName corresp="#p_PEV_1">Paz</persName>.</p>
                    <p>In the event President <persName corresp="#p_PEV_1">Paz</persName> decides
                        that he requires more than money and technical assistance we would wish to
                        consider his request in the multilateral framework of the <gloss
                            target="#t_OAS_1">OAS</gloss>. We would be most reluctant to act
                        unilaterally. With regard to a possible <gloss target="#t_OAS_1">OAS</gloss>
                        response, we must recognize there may be certain problems arising out of
                        Bolivia’s withdrawal from the Council, aside from those deriving from the
                        inherent reluctance of many members to “interfere” in the affairs of a
                        neighboring state.</p>
                    <p>We will be awaiting the Ambassador’s recommendations as well as General
                        O’Meara’s comments in response to <persName corresp="#p_SBS_1"
                            >Stephansky</persName>’s messages. It should be noted that the
                        Ambassador stopped in Panama last week for consultation with the
                        General.</p>
                </frus:attachment>
